	                    Policing Operation, Edinburgh


	                    <span id="Template_ctl08_lblMessage"><font color="Red"></font></span>

	                </h1>
                	
<table summary="box">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Three men have been arrested as part of a partnership operation
to tackle drug crime and associated problems in the South and East
of Edinburgh.<br />
<br />
<p>At around 10am yesterday (Tuesday 17 July 2012) officers from
the Lothian and Borders Police Safer Neighbourhood Team, Specialist
Support Unit, and CID carried out searches at four addresses in
Viewcraig Gardens and one address in Dumbiedykes Road.<br />
<br />
The activity followed months of intelligence-gathering within the
local community to identify individuals involved in the
distribution of drugs and resulted in a 28-year-old man being
arrested and charged under the Misuse of Drugs Act.<br />
<br />
Personal amounts of cannabis and other drug paraphernalia were also
recovered during the searches and a 49-year-old man was arrested on
an outstanding arrest warrant and charged with an alleged police
assault.<br />
<br /></p>
<p>Following the enforcement phase, Environmental Wardens and
Crimestoppers officials joined Community Officers to carry out
high-visibility patrols to engage with the public and offer
reassurance.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Leaflets detailing the operation were handed to local residents
and businesses to urge anyone with information relating to further
drug crime in the area to come forward.<br />
<br /></p>
<p>Officers then identified and arrested a 22-year-old man, who was
wanted on an outstanding warrant.<br />
<br /></p>
<p>In the coming weeks, Safer Neighbourhood Team Officers and
council representatives will continue their engagement with the
public during 'Quality of Life' meetings.<br />
<br /></p>
<p>During these meetings, residents will be encouraged to come
forward if they have any information relating to crime in their
area or if they want to discuss local issues or concerns.<br />
<br /></p>
<p>Detective Inspector Stuart Harkness said: "When Lothian and
Borders Police launched Community Commitment in September 2010, we
made a promise to listen to the public on the issues that affect
them locally and respond accordingly.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>"Over the past few months we have received vital information
from members of the public and used this to carry out yesterday's
operation.<br />
<br /></p>
<p>"Our activity has undoubtedly impacted upon local drug-dealing
and sends a clear message to our communities that we will continue
to act on any intelligence they provide us with to remove criminals
from their area.<br />
<br /></p>
<p>"We recognise that stemming the drug flow within an area can
impact upon other members of the community and so we're working
alongside our various partners to provide all the necessary support
and assistance.<br />
<br /></p>
<p>"Anyone with information relating to drug crime in their
community can contact their local policing team or alternatively
report the matter anonymously via the charity Crimestoppers on 0800
555 111."</p>
